org.chronos.chronodb.api.builder.query

Interface QueryBuilderFinalizer

  • All Known Subinterfaces:
    FinalizableQueryBuilder
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbstractFinalizableQueryBuilder, StandardQueryBuilderFinalizer

    public interface QueryBuilderFinalizer
    Represents a final part in the query builder API, i.e. one that allows to actually execute the previously built query.

    • Method Detail

      • getKeys

        java.util.Iterator<QualifiedKey> getKeys()
        Executes the previously built query.

        Usage example: 

         Iterator<QualifiedKey> iterator = tx.find().where("name").contains("hello").getKeys();
        Returns:
        An iterator over all keys that match the query. May be empty, but never null.

      • getKeysAsSet

        default java.util.Set<QualifiedKey> getKeysAsSet()
        Executes the previously built query.

        Please note that this method requires to completely exhaust the result iterator. For certain backends, this might be an expensive operation. It is recommended to use getKeys() in favor of this method whenever possible, as it can lazily fetch the results on-demand.

        Usage example: 

         Set<QualifiedKey> resultSet = tx.find().where("name").contains("hello").getKeysAsSet();
        Returns:
        An immutable set of all keys that match the query. May be empty, but never null.

      • getQualifiedResult

        java.util.Iterator<java.util.Map.Entry<QualifiedKey,java.lang.Object>> getQualifiedResult()
        Executes the previously built query.

        Usage example: 

         Iterator<Entry<QualifiedKey, Object>> iterator = tx.find().where("name").contains("hello").getQualifiedResult();
 // now simply iterate over the result...
 while (iterator.hasNext()) {
        Entry<QualifiedKey, Object> entry = iterator.next();
        QualifiedKey qKey = entry.getKey();
        Object value = entry.getValue();
        // ... do something with them
 }
        Returns:
        An iterator over all qualified key-value pairs that match the query. May be empty, but never null.

      • getResult

        java.util.Iterator<java.util.Map.Entry<java.lang.String,java.lang.Object>> getResult()
        Executes the previously built query.

        Usage example: 

         Iterator<Entry<String, Object>> iterator = tx.find().where("name").contains("hello").getResult();
 // now simply iterate over the result...
 while (iterator.hasNext()) {
        Entry<String, Object> entry = iterator.next();
        String key = entry.getKey();
        Object value = entry.getValue();
        // ... do something with them
 }

        WARNING:
        The result set of this method will contain all key-value combinations that match the query. If the query considers more than one keyspace, then the returned keys are not guaranteed to be unique. The reason is that a single key can simultaneously appear in multiple keyspaces with potentially different values. To disambiguate this situation, please consider using getQualifiedResult() if you are dealing with queries across keyspaces.

        Returns:
        An iterator over all key-value pairs that match the query. May be empty, but never null.
        See Also:
        getQualifiedResult()

      • getValues

        java.util.Iterator<java.lang.Object> getValues()
        Executes the previously built query.

        Usage example: 

         Iterator<Object> iterator = tx.find().where("name").contains("hello").getValues();
 // now simply iterate over the result...
 while (iterator.hasNext()) {
        Object value = iterator.next();
        // ... do something with it
 }

        WARNING: The returned iterator delivers the values for all key-value pairs that match the query. It is not guaranteed that any of the values will be unique!

        Returns:
        An iterator over all values that match the query. May be empty, but never null.

      • getValuesAsSet

        default java.util.Set<java.lang.Object> getValuesAsSet()
        Executes the previously built query.

        Please note that this method requires to completely exhaust the result iterator. For certain backends, this might be an expensive operation. It is recommended to use getValues() in favor of this method whenever possible, as it can lazily fetch the results on-demand.

        Usage example: 

         Set<Object> resultSet = tx.find().where("name").contains("hello").getValuesAsSet();
 // now simply iterate over the result...
 for (Object result : resultSet) {
        // ... do something with it
 }
        Returns:
        An immutable set containing the objects returned by the query. May be empty, but never null.
